Name: 2_restaurant_food_chef_recipes
Representative_Docs: ['“Was New York City a better place when there were sad old men sitting at the bar in the lobby of the Gramercy alongside stooped former artist’s models, with smoke curling up toward the ceiling on exhalations of gin breath and despair?” asks Sam Sifton. “Probably not. But the era is worth recalling as you sit at Maialino, drinking prosecco or coffee and looking south toward Gramercy Park as cabs inch past.” The latest venture from the restaurateur Danny Meyer is a Roman-style trattoria at the Gramercy Park Hotel, whose name is Italian for little pig. Pork is of course on the menu, but so is stracciatella, the Roman chicken soup with thick strands of egg; cold antipasti; and entrees including “a moist and flavorful plate of swordfish with mushrooms and fennel fronds, and another of crisp deviled chicken with black pepper and pickled chilies.” Enjoy them at a table or at the bar, “long, wide and walnut, maybe the most cordial surface the designer, David Rockwell, has ever put into a restaurant.” Or try the restaurant’s pièce de résistance, maialino al forno. “The skin, blasted to crisp in a hot oven, is dusted in rosemary, cracked fennel, salt and pepper: an apparently unambitious preparation that tastes just great.”', '“Was New York City a better place when there were sad old men sitting at the bar in the lobby of the Gramercy alongside stooped former artist’s models, with smoke curling up toward the ceiling on exhalations of gin breath and despair?” asks Sam Sifton. “Probably not. Name: 114_boat_ship_cruise_voyage
Representative_Docs: ['An article on Feb. 14 about what’s new in cruising in 2010 misstated the itinerary of the new Queen Elizabeth’s maiden voyage this fall. The ship’s maiden voyage, departing Oct. 12, sails from Southampton, England, to the Canary Islands in the Atlantic \x97 not to the Mediterranean. Its second voyage, departing Oct. 25, sails from Southampton through the Mediterranean to Naples, Italy. And a picture caption misidentified the river on which a Viking River Cruises vessel is shown sailing as it passes the Schloss Johannisburg in Aschaffenburg, Germany. It is the Main, not the Danube. ', ' Growing up, my only experience with cruises was watching the Pacific Princess set sail each week on “The Love Boat.” As an adult, I couldn’t imagine being on vacation and having to pack formal wear for dinner at the captain’s table, so I didn’t think cruising would ever be in my future. But my partner and I have friends who love it, so we joined them recently for a Freestyle Cruise on Norwegian Cruise Line. We sailed from Miami on the Pearl for a week, stopping in Roatan, Belize and Cozumel. Like the mighty seas, the trip had its ups and downs. First, a down: The check-in line to board the ship stretched out the door and into the scorching Miami sun and moved so slowly that by the time we got to the counter, neither of us was in the mood for the clerk’s corny banter. “You’re George and Steve? Are you sure?” I’m pretty sure our faces told him, “Let’s keep this moving before someone gets hurt.” The same thing — a slow-moving line a mile long — happened when we disembarked, too.', ' Growing up, my only experience with cruises was watching the Pacific Princess set sail each week on “The Love Boat.” As an adult, I couldn’t imagine being on vacation and having to pack formal wear for dinner at the captain’s table, so I didn’t think cruising would ever be in my future.
